  "descriptions": [
    {
      "descrType": "Overview",
      "description": "The AIM-120 Advanced Medium-Range Air-to-Air Missile (AMRAAM) is an American beyond-visual-range air-to-air missile capable of all-weather day-and-night operations. It uses active radar homing in the terminal phase of flight, allowing the launching aircraft to disengage after firing. The AMRAAM entered service in 1991 and is operated by the United States and over 40 allied nations. The current production variant, the AIM-120D, offers significantly extended range and improved guidance compared to earlier variants.",
      "shortDescription": "Active-radar-homing beyond-visual-range air-to-air missile operated by the US and 40+ allies.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Design",
      "description": "The AIM-120 has a cylindrical body with four delta control fins at the rear and four fixed fins at mid-body. Propulsion is a single-stage solid-fuel rocket motor. Guidance is inertial with mid-course uplink correction and active radar homing in the terminal phase; the launch aircraft can provide updates via datalink but need not continue to illuminate the target. The AIM-120D variant adds a two-way datalink, GPS-aided inertial navigation and a 50% increase in range over the AIM-120C-7. Warhead is a high-explosive blast-fragmentation type.",
      "shortDescription": "Cylindrical airframe with active radar terminal homing and solid-fuel rocket motor.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Usage",
      "description": "The AMRAAM has been used in combat by multiple air forces and has the highest kill record of any air-to-air missile in the post-Cold War era. It is the primary beyond-visual-range weapon for F-22, F-35, F-15, F-16, F/A-18, Eurofighter Typhoon, Gripen, and many other Western aircraft. Surface-launched versions (NASAMS, SLAMRAAM) extend the missile to ground-based air defense roles.",
      "shortDescription": "Primary BVR weapon for most Western aircraft; also deployed in ground-based NASAMS launchers.",
      "classification": "U"
    }
  ],
